# Celestial Blueprint File Format

Blueprints are **portable markdown files** with YAML frontmatter + a sectioned body. They round-trip between disk (markdown), the backend (JSON API), and the DB (SQLite) without information loss. **Markdown is canonical** — the SQLite DB is a rebuildable query index. If the DB is lost, `POST /blueprints/import` rebuilds it from the markdown.

---

## Round-Trip Contract

```
markdown file  ←→  backend JSON API  ←→  SQLite DB
     ↑
  git-tracked, Obsidian-readable, agent-readable
```

Mutating API endpoints always rewrite the markdown file. `GET /blueprints/{id}/export` regenerates it. `POST /blueprints/import` parses it back into the DB.

---

## Frontmatter Schema

Every blueprint file starts with YAML frontmatter:

```yaml
---
# --- Celestial Blueprint --- (machine fields)
id: bp_2026-06-23_my-project         # stable slug-id — also DB primary key
name: "My Project"                    # human display name
version: 0.1.0                        # semver — bumped on each [CHRONICLE CYCLE]
tier: small                           # small | medium | large | continuous
status: active                        # draft | active | blocked | shipped | archived
realm: 00_CORTEX/01_CREATION_REALM/Celestial_Blueprint/smart-folder.md  # path string

# --- workspace convention fields (required) ---
title: "My Project"                   # same as name (Obsidian/frontmatter standard)
tags: [planning, blueprint]
pipeline_stage: ideation              # ideation | extraction
date_created: 2026-06-23
modified: 2026-06-23

# --- optional metadata ---
model: haiku                          # tier-default model used
iterations: 3                         # iteration count so far
---
```

**Tier defaults:**
- `small` → model: haiku, iterations: 3+
- `medium` → model: sonnet, iterations: 2+
- `large` → model: opus, iterations: 1
- `continuous` → model: adaptive, iterations: ongoing

---

## Node Types (13)

Each node is a heading + an HTML-comment anchor carrying machine fields, plus a prose body.

| type | color | machine fields |
|------|-------|---------------|
| `text` | — | (none beyond base) |
| `metric` | blue | `value`, `unit`, `target`, `trend` (up/down/flat) |
| `chart` | — | `chart_type` (line/bar/area), `labels`, `data_json` |
| `list` | — | `ordered` (true/false) |
| `quote` | yellow | `author`, `source_url`, `confidence` (0–100) |
| `research` | yellow | `query`, `sources_json`, `confidence` (0–100) |
| `assumption` | red | `status` (unvalidated/validating/validated/invalidated), `risk` (low/med/high), `falsifier` |
| `decision` | — | `status` (accepted/rejected/deferred), `supersedes` |
| `chronicle` | — | `kind` (raw/cycle), `trigger`, `cycle` |
| `agent` | — | `agent_name`, `confidence` (0–100) |
| `cost` | — | `credits`, `model`, `optimization` |
| `realm` | — | `realm_path`, `soul_ref` |
| `tool` | — | `tool_name`, `maturity` (beta/stable/proven), `integration_cost` (low/med/high) |

**Base fields** (every node anchor): `id`, `cat` (category id), `type`

---

## Section Layout

```markdown
# [Blueprint Name]

<!-- bp:summary -->
One-paragraph summary of what this blueprint is for.

## Categories
- <!-- cat:c1 --> Validation
- <!-- cat:c2 --> Technical
- <!-- cat:c3 --> Market

## Nodes

### [Node Title]
<!-- node:text id=n1 cat=c2 -->
Free prose content for this node.

### Target Latency
<!-- node:metric id=n2 cat=c2 value=200 unit=ms target=150 trend=down -->
Why this metric matters and what it measures.

### Cold-Start is Tolerable
<!-- node:assumption id=n3 cat=c1 status=unvalidated risk=high falsifier="p95 > 2s in staging" -->
Rationale for why we believe this. What would prove it wrong.

### Use SQLite over Postgres
<!-- node:decision id=d_sqlite cat=c2 status=accepted supersedes=- -->
**Rationale:** Solo dev, no server needed, phone-as-VPS constraint.
**Alternatives rejected:** Postgres (ops cost), DuckDB (no full SQL support needed).

### Web Search — cold-start patterns
<!-- node:research id=rs1 cat=c1 query="sqlite wal mode performance solo" confidence=85 sources_json='[{"url":"...","domain":"sqlite.org"}]' -->
WAL mode gives ~4x write concurrency improvement. Confirmed default for this project.

## Assumptions
- <!-- assumption:a1 bp_ref=n3 status=unvalidated risk=high -->
  Cold-start latency is acceptable to users. Falsifier: p95 > 2s in production test.

## Decisions
- <!-- decision:d1 bp_ref=d_sqlite status=accepted date=2026-06-23 -->
  Use SQLite over Postgres — solo dev, no server. Alternatives: Postgres (rejected: ops cost).

## Risks

| id | risk | likelihood | impact | mitigation | status |
|----|------|-----------|--------|-----------|--------|
| r1 | DB lock under concurrent cron | med | high | WAL mode + retry wrapper | open |
<!-- risk-table -->

## Research Log
- <!-- research:rs1 query="sqlite wal performance" date=2026-06-23 -->
  WAL gives 4x write concurrency. Confirmed sufficient for solo dev.

## Chronicle Links
- <!-- chronicle:ch1 type=raw -->  chronicles/raw/2026-06-23-1-assumption-challenged.md
- <!-- chronicle:ch2 type=cycle --> chronicles/cycles/1/session-001.md

## Edges
<!-- edges -->
- n2 -> n3 (informs)
- n3 -> d_sqlite (drives)
- rs1 -> d_sqlite (evidence)

## Version Log
<!-- versions -->
- 0.1.0 — 2026-06-23 — initial Small-tier blueprint
```

---

## HTML-Comment Anchor Rules

- The comment anchor is the **machine-truth** (parsed into SQLite columns).
- Prose after the anchor is **human-truth** (stored as `body` TEXT blob in the DB).
- Unknown keys in a comment are preserved verbatim in the `data` JSON column (forward-compatible).
- Prose can be freely edited by humans without breaking parse, as long as comment anchors are not modified.
- Comment anchors are invisible in rendered Obsidian/markdown views.

---

## Storage Locations

```
blueprints/
  bp_2026-06-23_my-project.md          ← single-file (Small/Medium tier)
  bp_2026-06-23_large-project/
    blueprint.md                         ← folder (Large/Continuous tier)
    appendix-research.md
    appendix-financials.md

chronicles/
  raw/
    2026-06-23-1-assumption-challenged.md
    2026-06-23-2-decision-made.md
  cycles/
    1/
      session-001.md
```

---

## Blueprint ID Convention

`bp_{YYYY-MM-DD}_{slug}` where slug is kebab-case from the blueprint name.

Examples:
- `bp_2026-06-23_temporal-snowflake`
- `bp_2026-06-24_celestial-blueprint-phase-2`

---

## Tier Output Shape

### Small
```
5–10 bullet-point nodes
3 assumption nodes
2–3 open question nodes
1 recommendation/decision node
No charts or financials
```

### Medium
```
5 categories (Validation, Technical, Market, Business, Scaling)
5–8 nodes per category
Research-backed nodes (research type with sources)
Assumption register (3+ assumptions with risk ratings)
Risk table
1 decision log entry
```

### Large
```
All Medium content plus:
40+ nodes total
Metric nodes with charts
Financial projections (metric/chart nodes)
Full risk matrix
Technical architecture diagram (text node with ASCII or description)
Agent-performance notes
PDF-export-ready structure
```

### Continuous
```
Living version of any tier
Auto-appends new nodes at decision/assumption/risk events
Decision log grows over time
Assumption statuses evolve
Risk matrix updates weekly
Version log tracks all changes
```
